Orientation: L1 vs L2

Model Building

We set up a categorical variable, LangLev, to inform about the speakers L1 and L2 and a another categorical variable, Type, to inform about the Type of question MATCH and MISMATCH. Further, each different question is identified by the variable Trial that we treat also as a categorical variable, since we assume no influence of the order in which the question was posed. We record in the variable List the list from which the question is drawn, that is, list A or list B. The response variable is reaction time measured in milliseconds.

We are not intersted in the effect of the specific trials or the specific subjects. However, we are interested in knowing whether these effects are important for the variance of responses. Hence, we specify a mixed effects model with random effects associated to the factors Trial and Subject and fixed effects associated with the other factors. Due to the fact that we split trials between two lists and administered the two lists to different subjects the random effects of Trial and Subject are nested within List. Further, for the way we split trials, Trial is nested also within Type. Within the nesting structure subjects and questions are fully crossed. We fit our model in R using the package lme4 [Douglas Bates, Martin Maechler, Ben Bolker, Steve Walker (2015). Fitting Linear Mixed-Effects Models Using lme4. Journal of Statistical Software, 67(1), 1-48. doi:10.18637/jss.v067.i01]. As far as the fixed effects are concerned, we are interested in the fixed effects of LangLev, Type and their interaction. We expect no effect by List but we include it in the model to test our expectation.

The distribution of reaction times has longer tail on the right and never reaches zero. Under these conditions, logarithm transformation or generalized linear mixed models with Gamma family and log link function are common approaches to meet the assumptions underlying mixed linear models. In our case, we found that a log-transformed response variable improved considerably the diagnostic plots (conditional and marginal residual qqplots) of the selected models. A Gamma family transformation with log link function yield much worse diagnostic plots.

Hence, considering the design explained above and the goals of this study we analyze the following model is:

lmm<- lmer(log(Time) ~ Type + LangLev + List + Type:LangLev + (1 | List:Subject)+ (1 | List:Type:Trial),
           data = DLM, REML=FALSE)

Analysis of Variance

In the following, we report the Anova of type III with Satterwhite approximation to take into account the different sizes of samples in the experimental units. We note that in the literature the use of this procedure is controversial, however, we observe here that the results confirm those of likelihood ratio tests.

Note that due to the removal of entries with missing values, our experimental set up is not balanced. Hence, it is controversial to report p-values for F or t statistics as there are no analytical results for null distributions of parameter estimates in complex situations (e.g., unbalanced or partially crossed designs) [Bates 2015].

The package lmerTest makes availbale an analysis of variance of Type III with Satterthwaite approximation for degrees of freedom.

require(lmerTest)
lmm<- lmer(log(Time) ~ Type + LangLev + List + Type:LangLev + (1 | List:Subject)+ (1 | List:Type:Trial),
           data = DLM, REML=FALSE)
anova(lmm)

We observe that the two random effects, subjects and trials, account for a good portion of the standard deviation of the residuals 0.392, namely, for 0.253 and 0.151, respectively. The model is translated by means of a significant intercept. The estimated effects are in the log transformed scale.

These results on the statistical significance of the terms are confirmed also by backward elimination of non-significant effects and by boostrap confidence intervals:

We also observed the analysis by the merTools package that calculates simulated values of the (fixed and random) effects from the posterior using the function arm::sim:

detach("package:lmerTest",unload=TRUE)
require(merTools)
lmm <- lmer(formula = log(Time) ~ Type + LangLev + List + Type:LangLev + (1 | List:Subject) + 
    (1 | List:Type:Trial), data = DLM, REML = FALSE)
plotREsim(REsim(lmm, n.sims= 100), level=0.95, stat="mean", sd = TRUE)

plotFEsim(FEsim(lmm, n.sims = 100), level = 0.95, stat = 'mean', intercept = FALSE, sd=TRUE)

These plots also confirm our conclusions that Type, List and Type:LangLev are not significant.

Conclusions

We plot the random and the fixed effects together with their 95% confidence levels in the figure. The confidence levels are obtained by the estimated standard deviation and the normal distribution. However, other analysis with boostrapped confidence intervals confirmed the same conclusions.

From the figure we can observe that the random effects cause often a significant effect by shifting the intercept by a quantity larger than zero. For the fixed effects we transformed back the effects in the linear time scale of milliseconds. It is evident that L1 speakers have a shorter reaction time and that Type and List do not have a significant impact.

Diagnostic plots

The joint qqplot looks normal. The marginal look less compliant with the normality assumptions.
